  <text xml:space="preserve">Employee Name: _____________________________________ Manager Name: _______________________________________ Satisfaction Criteria Satisfaction Level Satisfaction Level Satisfaction Level Comments Initial Review Checkpoint 1 Checkpoint 2 1. 2. 3. 4. 5. Satisfaction Level: VS-Very Satisfied; S-Satisfied; D-Dissatisfied Do you appreciate receiving recognition from your manager on special dates such as birthdays, service anniversaries? Yes___ No____ Initial Review - Overall Satisfaction Level: ____ Employee/Dated __________________ Manager/Dated __________________________ Checkpoint 1 - Overall Satisfaction Level: ____ Employee/Dated __________________ Manager/Dated __________________________ Checkpoint 2 - Overall Satisfaction Level: ____ Employee/Dated __________________ Manager/Dated __________________________ Building a successful relationship, understanding the following: Achieving a personal relationship . What motivates you? Achieving career goals . How satisfied are you with your opportunity to get a better job in IBM? Achieving high performance and recognition . I am rewarded according to my performance. ==Instructions== ===Guidance For Using the "Fit For You" Card=== The "Fit For You" card is an aid for both employees and managers to establish a productive and rewarding relationship. It is a highly recommended tool to improve Manager / Employee communications. The process can be initiated by either the employee or the manager. It is an agreement between the manager and the employee that promotes an environment of open and honest communication regarding what motivates and encourages the employee and will increase their overall satisfaction. This process can be used as frequently as desired to ensure effective communications are maintained. This approach sets the stage for effective employee / manager communications and helps both parties attain a realistic understanding of expectations. It clears the air on the employee's conditions of satisfaction. It legitimizes a dialogue that can be an excellent rapport-building experience. It will set up ground rules for the manager-employee working relationship throughout the year, and proactively help improve the employee.s engagement, motivation, and overall satisfaction. Minor irritants can be eliminated before they become major concerns. This is a good opportunity for the manager to demonstrate interest in each employee, especially those who are remote or mobile. Personal contact is valuable in this activity, but when face-to-face meetings are not possible, telephone conversations can be effective. A simple to use, but powerful tool, the "Fit For You" card is one of the most, if not the most, powerful culture-shaping tools. The degree of its use will correlate closely with the level of high-performance climate in a unit. ===Process Details=== Initial Review of the .Fit For You. to establish Satisfaction Criteria 1. The Manager or the Employee schedules a meeting for discussion of the .Fit For You.. 2. The employee meets with the manager and discusses the environment which enables the employee to increase productivity and job satisfaction. The Suggested Satisfaction Criteria Topics (below) provide a helpful starter set for the discussion - but don.t be constrained by them. 3. The employee may bring in the form with some criteria already filled in, or may be more comfortable filling in the criteria during the session. Note that the Satisfaction Criteria are what the employee is looking for from the manager, not vice versa. These criteria are written in the first column: Satisfaction Criteria. 4. The Satisfaction Level in the Initial Review column is filled in with the employee.s initial rating of how satisfied they are with that item. Just because it is on the form does not mean the employee is satisfied with it. The last column provides the opportunity for additional detail on why the rating is what it is, and how the manager can improve it. 5. An Overall Satisfaction Level rating is initially provided. 6. The employee and the manager agree on the 1st Checkpoint period. 7. The employee and the manager both sign and date the form. The employee makes a copy for the manager and keeps the original. Periodic Checkpoint to rate Employee Satisfaction against Set Criteria 1. The Employee and Manager reconvene to discuss the status of the previously agreed to criteria. The appropriate Checkpoint column is filled in with the employee.s rating of how satisfied they are with that item at the current point in time. At this point in time, the employee should not feel that they must enter a VS rating and should explain in the last column why the rating is what it is, and how the manager can improve it. e.g. Perhaps the Employee rated Work/Life balance as their number one criteria for satisfaction. However the rating they gave is S for Satisfied. The comments might say something to clarify why S and not VS. Also they might describe the perfect Work/Life balance situation for them where they would give a VS. Everybody has different criteria to make them a satisfied employee, so it is important to clarify and be sure the manager understands what the employee is looking for. 2. An Overall Satisfaction Level rating for the Checkpoint period is provided. 3. The employee and the manager agree on the next suitable Checkpoint period or whether a new Fit For You card should be initiated for a new year. 4. The employee and the manager both sign and date the form. The employee makes a copy for the manager and keeps the original. ===Suggested Satisfaction Criteria Topics:=== Things that motivate: e.g. What conditions lead to the employee.s highest level of buy-in and commitment? What gets the employee excited and enthusiastically productive? Recognition and reward: e.g. Preferred kind of recognition? Importance of money? Individual or Team? Public or Private? With or without partner/spouse? Interests/Passions - assignments/career: e.g. What does the employee want to do next, and how can the manager help? What are your key passions? How can the manager help support the employee.s volunteer and/or extra-curricular activities? (This discussion may lead to an IDP discussion, which is fine) Communications preferences: e.g. Phonemail, Sametime, e-mail, face-to-face preferences? .Hidden message. in pre-dawn or late-night communications? Styles ... chatty, net, etc.? What to copy each other on? Support requirements: e.g. Managerial support desired? Administrative support options? Technology needs? Mentoring needs or possibilities? .Buddy. needs? Feedback requirements: e.g. Prior agreement on how/when to give each other difficult feedback or positive feedback (that is different from recognition)? Frequency of meetings, and who sets them up? Working relationship: e.g. The manager.s role ... what the employee needs from the manager? Work/Life: e.g. How does the employee manage work/life requirements? How can the manager help? Culture: e.g. How does the employee.s cultural background come into play? Are there cultural differences? Life Event: e.g. Is there change or needs in your personal life that require focus (e.g. an illness in the family, an upcoming wedding/commitment ceremony, a major anniversary, etc.) Other special occasion? Environment: How can the manager help the employee work more effectively? Some employees need quiet time for heads down kind of work. Where is the best location for the employee to work during these times? How/what does the manager and the employee need to change to accommodate this difference in working location? [[Category:IBM]] [[Category:Contract]]</text> 
