  <comment>New page: This is a sample of objectives for the various bands/levels based upon job AIS/AMS Calgary 2008 Personal Business Commitments (PBC) Sample Goals for Application Se...</comment> 
  <text xml:space="preserve">This is a sample of objectives for the various bands/levels based upon job AIS/AMS Calgary 2008 Personal Business Commitments (PBC) Sample Goals for Application Services (AS) Practitioners Mar. 2008 Guidance and Instructions Profile Holding Manager should conduct a minimum of 3 reviews during the year with each employee. . Initial review with employee where the PBC is agreed upon /customized. Both manager and employee should discuss the differences in the PBC process. The PBC is not process based, but rather relationship based. It is essential for both manager and employee to understand this aspect of the PBC process. . Mid-year review with employee to give trending feedback . Final year-end review, where employee receives their final evaluation. Please do the following at the initial review . Review this document . Manager and employee agree upon goals for employee during the year . Add new items to the custom objectives (tasks which have been assigned to you, which are not specifically covered) . Document agreed upon goals in the PBC Business Goals /Developmental section of the PBC Web Tool. Web Tool is found at https://w3-1.ibm.com/hr/americas/pbc/index.jsp . Revise as required based on your Manager.s feedback. Later in the year: . Mid-year: plan a progress review with your Manager . End of year: . Complete the results sections of the PBC Tool, and forward the revised document to your Manager . Schedule final review with your Manager . Provide feedback from peers, as requested PBC Ratings In preparation for your PBC review, please take a moment to familiarize yourself with IBM.s PBC ratings. The following should help your discussion with your manager. You may also wish to review the job description for your position and band in the Position Reference Library. Your Final Evaluation: You will receive a performance evaluation from your manager. Notes: While your evaluation is delivered by your manager, the decision is made by the entire management team. The evaluation process a relative ranking exercise ... a comparison to your peers. You are being evaluated within the context of the entire GBS - Application Services organization. Fairness is a key component of the process. Evaluations are not taken lightly by the management team. The emphasis is on results, not effort. Factors influencing your Evaluation A number of factors go into your evaluation, they include: . The employee.s full range of job responsibilities and band . Peer feedback . Client feedback (COSCARD etc.) . Observations of Managers, Practice Leads and Project Managers . Results compared to results of others with similar responsibilities and band . Impact of the employee.s results on the organization . Attitude that was displayed throughout the year Position Reference Library It is useful to review the job Position Reference Library to see the expectations of an employee in your position and band. General guidance for expectations placed on professionals can be found in the position reference library. These documents effectively compare and contrast the expectations of one band to another and one profession to another. The Position Reference Library is found at http://w3.can.ibm.com/hr/prl/index.html IBM.s 5-Tier Rating System Your manager assigns a rating based on your results and behaviors, as well as all other relevant factors, in achieving your Personal Business Commitment objectives. PBC 1 - Among the top contributors this year: Achieves exceptional results; as a 1 performer, clearly stands out from the rest; is a role model for the IBM Values. PBC 2+ -Above average contributor: Goes above and beyond job responsibilities; outperforms most peers; finds ways to grow scope and impact. PBC 2 - Solid contributor: Consistently meets job responsibilities; is reliable in doing job. Demonstrate appropriate level of knowledge, skill, effectiveness and initiative. PBC 3 - Among the lowest contributors, need to improve: When compared to others: Does not fully execute all job responsibilities, or executes responsibilities, but with lower degree of results and/or Does not demonstrate as high a level of knowledge, skill, effectiveness, or initiative. Consecutive ratings at the PBC 3 level are unacceptable in IBM's high performance culture and require improvement. PBC 4- Unsatisfactory: Does not demonstrate or utilize knowledge and skill required; does not execute against job responsibilities; and/or shows no significant improvement after consecutive PBC 3 ratings. Immediate, significant and sustained improvement has to be demonstrated, otherwise separation from IBM will result. IBM is a Value Driven Organization with a Goal Driven PBC Process. These samples were developed to provide a basis for GBS Application Services employees to create their own PBC for the year 2008. . These are sample PBC goals -- representative of commitments appropriate to each of the roles o There is not sample for every role, but rather for positions which represent the most common roles . The PBC objectives used need to be tailored to your individual role . Your PBC should identify important desired business goals, with a target or method to measure these goals . Work with your Manager to finalize your goals Visit . GBS & Me . Canada . http://w3-03.ibm.com/services/gbs/americas/gbs_me/canada/index.html for additional information on setting goals and guidance on the PBC process. . Your PBC is documented in the web-based PBC tool. To create your PBC, . Visit: https://w3-1.ibm.com/hr/americas/pbc/index.jsp and log on by using your current IBM intranet userid and password. . Use .save and exit. to keep your PBC in .Draft mode. until you have completed your PBC goal discussions with your Manager. PCO - Band 5 5 PCO/Associate Project Manager - Band 6/7 8 Advisory Project Manager - Band 8 10 Senior Project Manager - Band 9 12 IT Specialist . Band 6 15 Advisory IT Specialist - Band 7 17 Senior IT Specialist . Band 8 19 Consulting IT Specialist - Band 9 21 IT Specialist . Band 6 ( Business Analyst ) 23 Advisory IT Specialist - Band 7 ( Business Analyst ) 25 Senior IT Specialist . Band 8 ( Business Analyst ) 27 Consulting IT Specialist - Band 9 ( Business Analyst ) 29 Associate IT Architect - Band 7 31 Advisory IT Architect - Band 8 33 Senior IT Architect - Band 9 35 Consultant . Band 7 37 Senior Consultant - Band 8 39 Managing Consultant - Band 9 41 The 7 People Management Indicators 44 Foundational Competencies for ALL Practitioners 45 Leadership Competencies for Intermediate/Senior Roles 46 PCO - Band 5 Business Goals: What are your business goals for this assessment period? Make sure your goals align with IBM.s strategy and IBM.s values, your business unit goals, and your department goals. Understand and support the IBM GBS 3D Strategy of Differentiated Solutions, Deeper Client Relationships and Delivered Globally. (1) Differentiated Solutions: (1.1) Work with your peers and other professionals to share experiences, transfer skills and learning, and support each other in growing IBM business. (2) Deeper Client Relationships: (2.1) Contribute to the fulfilment of IBM and overall engagement commitments resulting in very satisfied clients. Meet or exceed Conditions of Satisfaction as measured by EoE and Project Assessments. Ensure high quality deliverables. (3) Delivered Globally (and Locally): (3.1) Contribute positively to the financial and utilization targets of 83.7/92.7% for our AS Calgary Practice. My personal target will be xx%. (3.2) Ensure compliance with IBM Business processes: Full-labour Claiming, Expenses, PD Tool Skill Assessments, updated Resume, WST and PBC/IDP. (3.3) Assist in achievement and the maintaining of effective Business Controls. Assist in the achievement of satisfactory quarterly controls; Key Control Over operations (KCO), Corporate Audits, Business Controls proactive reviews, Data Security and Privacy practices and ensure NO Qualified SAS70 or AUP reports. (3.4) Demonstrate understanding and compliance with Delivery Excellence; AMS Best Practices, Customer Satisfaction-ICES, ICHC, COScards, Financial Management, Project & Portfolio Management, and Risk Management. https://w3.webahead.ibm.com/w3ki/display/DECANADA/Home Assist in the achievement of consistent usage of Globally Integrated End-to-End process, methods, metrics and tools to drive DE. Assist in maintaining compliance to the appropriate industry standards . CMMI, ITIL, SOX. Demonstrate adherence to GBS and AS Policies. 4. Additional AS Calgary & role specific goals: - Attend and provide feedback to quarterly department meetings. Attendance via phone or in person is expected. - Participate/lead in giveback activities: Spirit Events, Calgary IBM Club, Mentoring, Lunch n Learns, Other Community Events (e.g. Junior Achievement) - Provide timely and constructive feedback both informally and on Feedback forms (EOE, Project Assessment) - Expenses to be submitted within 60 days of expense occurring. ILC to be submitted by Friday Noon. 5. Perform the following PCO duties as defined by current engagement: Financial Management . Initialize financial forecast information into BCS Portfolio Management Data Base . Update financial forecasts on a monthly basis in BCS Portfolio Management Database (reflect all changes from approved change requests) . Monitor expenses, revenues and costs to ensure that they are accurately reflected on the General Ledger . Ensure actual revenues and costs are reconciled to the original pricing plan . Ensure customer invoices are generated (either T&M or based on milestone payments) . Collect T&L and other expense documentation for customer invoicing . Monitor delinquent Accounts Receivable and initiate action with PM . Monitor ICA expenditures and end dates . Review CLAIM submissions for accuracy and reconcile issues with PM . Manage ILCA approvals for labor and expenditures . Ensure monthly revenue and cost accruals are submitted to the Regional Finance Contact . Interface with the Regional Finance Contact to ensure the integrity of the financial data Project Planning and Tracking . Setup Project Control Book and project delivery Notes database . Assist PM in establishment of a COSCard . Assist PM in project plan development . Assist PM in consolidating project team activity status and updating project plan tracking . Provide project plan status to PM for project status reporting . Schedule project review meetings, IPPRs and PMRs . Track deliverable sign-offs Contract Administration . Register contract with CSO and obtain Work numbers . Archive ESL (if applicable) and signed contract . Monitor end dates of ESL/contract and funds availability -- advise PM/Principal for action . Register with CSO change requests affecting contract terms Project Communication . Assist PM in creation of project status reports . Implement and maintain project orientation information for new project staff Change Management . Logging of all project change requests . Assist PM in tracking and follow-up of outstanding change requests . Assist PM in obtaining evaluations and sign-offs on change requests . Assist PM in preparation of regular change management reports Issue Management . Logging of all project issues as identified by project team members . Assist PM in tracking and maintaining outstanding issues . Initiation of escalation process where required . Assist PM in preparation of regular issue management reports Resource Management . Assist PM/Principal in preparation and submission of RRFs Subcontract Administration . Prepare subcontractors request forms . Subcontractor timesheet and invoice verification and tracking Project Closure . Collect and archive all project intellectual materials . Obtain and record COSCard results from PM/Principal . Obtain customer completion sign-off from PM/Principal . Confirm project closure with CSO . Support requests for project information for SACA and SDD audits People Management Goals: If you hav